	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=32254><span id= >Nixoh</span></a><br><span id=notbold>340 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [2.77]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>If you're contrasting the 3/tick with the damage done by the mobs, you're missing the point to the aura-line (now called simply regen 1,2 and 3) of worn effects.<br><br>First off, keep in mind these stack with all regen (including eachother).<br><br>Ok, now let's say that you have a shammy with 10 points worth of these (say, 3+3+2+1+1). That's 10HP/tick regen which works out to 9000 hit points worth of regen during a 90-minute LDON adventure. Go ask your shaman what he can do with 9000 hit points per adventure ;-) Better yet, go ask your shaman what he can do with an extra 1800 hit points per hour (which is what he gets from this augment alone without swapping out anything).<br><br>It's intended to be flowing-thought for hit-points, and flowing thought isn't all that useful on it's own, it's just a bump to your existing mana-regen from spells (like clarity, kei, lich, etc). Same goes for this, and it's one heck of a useful thing if you use it right. I would be shocked if even folks who have done PoTime would not want such a thing.<br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue Sep 30 15:24:12 2003</em></p>&nbsp;<br>You gain experience!<br>The Goblin Warlord hits YOU for 50 points!<br></td></td></tr>
